05544nam a22008775i 9780823264926DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20152015nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232649267 a10.1515/97808232649262doi  a(DE-B1597)551402  a(OCoLC)906575758  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aBH301.S43bF55 2015eb 7aSOC0320002bisacsh04a111/.852231 aNagel, Barbara Natalie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFlirtations :bRhetoric and Aesthetics This Side of Seduction /cBarbara Natalie Nagel, Lauren Shizuko Stone; Daniel Hoffman-Schwartz. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2015] 4cÂ©2015  a1 online resource (192 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aIdiom: Inventing Writing Theory00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- t"Almost Nothing; Almost Everything": An Introduction to the Discourse of Flirtation -- tINTERLUDE -- tThe Art of Flirtation: Simmel's Coquetry Without End -- t"The Double- Sense of the 'With' ": Rethinking Relation after Simmel -- tRhetoric's Flirtation with Literature, from Gorgias to Aristotle: The Epideictic Genre -- tPlaying with Yourself: On the Self-Reference of Flirtation -- tINTERLUDE -- tLife Is a Flirtation: Thomas Mann's Felix Krull -- tThe "Irreducibly Doubled Stroke": Flirtation, Felicity, and Sincerity -- tFrill and Flirtation: Femininity in the Public Space -- tLearning to Flirt with Don Juan -- tINTERLUDE -- tThe Luxury of Self- Destruction: Flirting with Mimesis with Roger Caillois -- tWartime Love Affairs and Deathly Flirtation: Freud and Caillois on Identifying with Loss -- tBestiality: Mediation More Ferarum -- tDoing It as the Beasts Did: Intertextuality as Flirtation in Gradiva -- tNotes -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat is flirtation, and how does it differ from seduction?In historical terms, the particular question of flirtation has tended to be obscured by that of seduction, which has understandably been a major preoccupation for twentieth-century thought and critical theory. Both the discourse and the critique of seduction are unified by their shared obsession with a very determinate end: power. In contrast, flirtation is the game in which no one seems to gain the upper hand and no one seems to surrender. The counter-concept of flirtation has thus stood quietly to the side, never quite achieving the same prominence as that of seduction. It is this elusive (and largely ignored) territory of playing for play's sake that is the subject of this anthology.The essays in this volume address the under-theorized terrain of flirtation not as a subgenre of seduction but rather as a phenomenon in its own right. Drawing on the interdisciplinary history of scholarship on flirtation even as it re-approaches the question from a distinctly aesthetic and literary-theoretical point of view, the contributors to Flirtations thus give an account of the practice of flirtation and of the figure of the flirt, taking up the act's relationship to issues of mimesis, poetic ambiguity, and aesthetic pleasure. The art of this poetic playfulness-often read or misread as flirtation's "empty gesture"-becomes suddenly legible as the wielding of a particular and subtle form of nonteleological power.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aAesthetics. 0aFlirting. 0aSeduction. 4aCaillois. 4aFlirtation. 4aFreud. 4aGorgias. 4aJensen. 4aSapeurs. 4aSimmel. 4aThomas Mann. 4aaesthetics. 4acritical theory. 4agender. 4amimesis. 4aseduction. 4asexuality. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh1 aHoffman-Schwartz, Daniel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 